  <class_name>SpectrallyEnhancedLighting</class_name>
  <display_name>Spectrally Enhanced Lighting</display_name>
  <description>Spectrally Enhanced Lighting is a design method that capitalizes on naturally occurring gains in visual efficiency as a consequence of the spectral content of higher CCT light sources. These gains can be translated directly into improved energy efficiency by employing lamps with higher CCT and Color Rendering Index (CRI), such as the 5000K, 80-85 CRI (850) lamp (1).  These lamps can be installed at lighting levels 20% lower than traditional linear fluorescent lighting without occupant acceptance issues.</description>
  <modeler_description>Find all of the lights in the building, and reduce their powers by the user-specified fraction (default 20%) This default comes from a DOE-funded study.  Do not apply this lighting power reduction in hospital operating rooms or other areas where lighting quality is not similar to that used in offices.</modeler_description>
